{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_ham_ver01/data/sn86090528/00295864667/1920100101/0223.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE EIGHT\nCHICKASHA DAILY EXPRESS, CH1CKA8HA OKLAHOMA FRIDAY, OCTOBER 1, 1920.\nChickasha Daily Express\nGEO. II. EVANS\nJ- EDWIN POOL\n...Publisher and Business Manager\nManaging Editor\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF GRADY COUNTY\nEntered at the Postoffice at Chickasha, Oklahoma, as seconil class\nmail matter\nCHICKASHA, OKLAHOMA,\nFRIDAY, OCTOBER 1, 1920.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE9\nOne yr. delivered by carrier $6.00\nSix months $3.00\nThree months $1.50\nOne month -60\nOne year by mail $4.00\nSix month by mail 2.00\nThree months by mail 1-00\nSingle copy 5c\nAny erroneous reflections on\nthe character of any person,\nfirm or corporation and any\nmisstatement which may ap\npear In the columns of the\nExpress will be gladly cor\nrected upon Its being brought\nto the attention of the\nmanagement.\nGives All The Local News\nNews By A. P. Wire Daily\nj\nEXPRE8S PACKAGETTES\nA Court or the League?\nThe International Court as organized by Mr. Hoot and Ids con\nfreres on the Commission and recently submitted to the Council of\nthe League of Nations for their action, provides that when a dispute\nlias arisen between nations which is found to be impossible to settle\nby diplomatic, -means or by an agreement to arbitrate, the complain\ning nation may bring the case before the International Court. The\ncourt shall decide first whether jurisdictional conditions have been\ncomplied with, and, if so, can hear and determine 1he dispute ac\ncording to the next article in the draft.\nThe next article provides that the court shall have jurisdiction\nto trv eases of a legal nature concerning the interpretation of trea\nties, questions of international law, breaches of international obliga\ntion and reparation for such breaches.\nThe question arises, where is Senator Harding to insert his\n\"teeth\" into this court if we have not the League of Nations?\nShall the court itself have power to force nations to submit their\ncases to it, and how is it going to enforce its decrees? Suppose one\nnation refuses to appear before the court, or. having appeared, re\nfuses to abide by its judgment?\nThe League of Nations Covenant, which provides by Article\nXir of the treaty for an International Court, provides penalties\nagainst nations which refuse to arbitrate their disputes or which\nrefuse to carry out the court's decision. As one of the instruments\nof the League of Nations, the International Court of Justice will be\na benefaction to the world. As a substitute for the League of Na\ntions, it would be an impotent and miserable failure.\no\nThe Work of the League.\nThe League of Nations is an accomplished fact, an existing and\nworking organization. It is administering the Saar Valley and the\ncity of Danzig. It is conducting a public-health campaign. to pro\ntect the world from typhus and other diseases and the- elimination\nof the opium trade. It has established an international labor bu\nreau and is settling international disputes. It has before it the form\ning of a great International Court of Justice, in the draft of which\nKlihu Hoot participated.\nOnly last week a dozen treaties wore registered with the League\nof Nations and were published by it under its provision that no\ntreaties should be binding until registered with the league and pub\nlished by it.\nOn Friday, September 18, while Harding and Johnson were in\nsisting that the league was dead beyond' resurrection, Sweden and\nFinland accepted Ihe intervention of the league for the settlement\nof the dispnte between them regarding the Aland Islands.-\nIn this connection Mr. Branting said:\n\"1 will not use the word 'war,' but the situation was tense.\nThe council of the league has dissipated the feeling.\n\"All that the league needs to make it a most effective and cer\ntain instrument of reducing future wars to the absolute minimum\nis the participation of the I'nited States. Sweden and the other na\ntions of pie world await the entrance of America with anxiety and\nthe keenest interest.\"\nThe League of Nations is not dead. The United States is going\nto ratify the treaty and become a member of it and vastly increase\nits power and its usefulness and make it a benefaction to the world\nand the guarantee of justice and peace.\nFor all that Is noble and high and\ngood\nHus an Influence on. the set;\nAnd the world is -better for every\none\nWho is living itt his best.\nSelected.\nHowdy, Jiinmie Cox. We're glad to\nsee you in Oklahoma but feel sorry\nfor you because you didn't Ret to\ncome to Chickasha.\nAnd we'll be happy to greet War\nren G. too when he visits our great\nstate. His politics may be punk but.\nlike Jiinmie, he's a regular fellah,\nCol Courtney, weather boss, has\njust completed the Installation ol\na new machine In his forecasting\ndepartment, which, he expects, will\nadd greatly to the efficiency of hij\nplant.\nAfter seeing that K1ks show, we\nare expecting any' minute to hear\nthat Fred Frey has massacreed John\nOwsley.\nAlso, we're thinking that the Rev.\nMr. Tootaker may have missed hid\ncalling. Ho could pull down a\nprincely salary on the stage.\nAnd Fat Fred Hamilton really\nought to go Into the black-face busi\nness. Si Simp Bays he notices that a\nfrost never hurts vegetables very\nmuch when it isn't heavy enough to\nkill. I\nIf the ed. of the Kxpress and llro.\nSchlotterbeck keep on writing let\nters about the League of Nations\nit won't be surprising to hear some\nbody suggest that they hire a hall.\nBut a better way would be to re\nfer the entire controversy to the Sl'-and-Argue\nclub which has supreme\njurisdiction In all such mighty matters.\nA 8TOLEN BMILE 'ER TWO\n\nHomeward Bound\nFolks are beginning to return\nfrom the summer resorts for a much\nneeded rest. PitUourg Sun.\nWhen Real Peace Comes.\nSome snappy day we shall beat our\nswords into plow shares, and our\njazz bands into unconsciousness.\nBaltimore Sun.\nQuestion of Hour.\nWill the hotel fhut the League of\nNations hus bought at Geneva be\nrun on the American or Kuropean\nplan? Providence Journal.\nTragedies of the Crime Wave.\nCook \"Cheer up, Liz! U ain't,\nyour fault If the silver was stolen!\nMaid \"N-no. but I'd just cleaned\nii all! \"-London Opinion.\nOur Fish.\nA petrified fish about ii ft y feel\nlong has been discovered in t'tah.\nThis is said to be the largest sar\ndine and the smallest whale Ameri\nca has ever produced.- Punk (London.)\nDEMOCRATIC COUNTY\nTICKET.\nFor County Judge:\nJ. E. Suelton f\nj For Sheriff:\nMatt Saukey\nFor County Attorney:\ni Ben Goff\nFor County Clerk:\nW. T. (Billy) Cloud\nI For' Court Clerk:\nI E. G (Curley) Reynolds\nFor County Treasurer:\ni L. A. Sanders\nFor County Superintendent:\nH. P. Allen\ni For Assessor:\nJ. D. Bryan\nFor County Weigher:\nA. (Sandy) Horton\nFor County Commissioners\nNorthern District\nT. M. McElroy\nCentral District\nDave Hybarger\nSouthern District\nSell Tursley\nNotice.\nI will sell one Twin Cylinder\nTlior Motor Cycle, No. 1.1a 1.1.19, in\nfront of 416 Kansas Avenue, Friday,\nOct. 1, 19:'0, at 2: SO p. m. for stor\nage and repairs. ft-20-10t.\nARCH M. BROWN.\nTypewriters\nIt will pay to investigate the FOX\nbefore you buy a typewriter. Many\nexclusive features. The Fox Is made\nlu standard and portable models;\nprompt delivery at present. Oakes\nTypewriter Exchange, state dealers,\n207 West Second street, Oklahoma\nCity. See machine at Dally Eipress.\nWALDORF\nICE CREAM\nis sanitary, Pasteur\nized and pure.\nTry it.\nCHICKASHA ICE CREAM CO.\n42? Kansas Vhom 300\nMORGAN STUDIO OF\nEXPRESSION\n1308 S. Seventh Street\n(Mrs. A. 13. Morgan, Teacher)\nEnrollment for credit pupils for\nFall Term closes September 10.\nPhone f42.\nAnyone wishing to take music les\nsons from J. A. Sager will find Mr\naager at Ihe Christian church en\nMondays, Tuesdays, Thursdays and\nFridays from 3 to 6 each week.\nE. L. DE HART\nSuccessor to\nAnother thing in the long run a\nwoman generally manages to win\nout when ishe gets Into an argument\nwith her alleged lord and master\nover a new house.\nVOICE PLACEMENT\nMrs. P. M. DeVore\n1410 Colo. Ave. Fhone 821.\nOpera Class Sat. A. M.\nPhone 481 116 N. 3rd St.\n11 AY JONES\nAuctioneer\nFarm Sales a Specialty.\nMinco, Okla.\nOur Situation.\nThe survey of business conditions recently completed by Hon.\nFranklin K. Lane, ex-secretary of the interior, is calculated to renew\nconfidence in the going powers of the I'nited States. In his sum\nmary of what he refers to as \"the first comprehensive, carefully\nmade and approximately accurate picture of industrial, agricultural,\nfinancial and political conditions in the United States,\" Mr. Lane\nstates that the inquiry was conducted by nine hundred field agents,\nembracing interviews with manufacturers, merchants, chambers of\ncommerce, bankers and lawyers.\nAll of these forces agree that the country is in a sound and\nhealthy condition, and is in a better situation than any other coun\ntry in the world. Where there is tightness shown in the money mar\nket is proof that the process of deflation is working. The high cost\nof living--too high by ajl odds is due to unequal distribution and\nmiddlemen. Mr. Lane's conclusion is:\n\"It is clear that the country is on a sound economic basis and\nthere is generally a spirit of confidence in the future, regardless of\nthe outcome of the election. The business outlook appears to le\ngood in every section. \"Wholesalers and retailers view the fall and\nwinter optimistically. The retailer is finding that the consumer is\nlooking forward without fear to the winter, and his purchases from\nthe wholesaler are founded upon this optimism. From Ihe simple\ntoiler up through to the tradesmen, to the industry and the finan\ncier there runs the connected feeling of confidence.\"\nAll that is needed to keep this country in its high condition of\nprosperity is team work on the part of all the people, and a curbing\nof the elements which seem bent .on the destruction of the establish\ned order. Rochester News.\no\nIn opposing the suggested revocation of corporation charters\nin Oklahoma Champbell Russell may be dead right, but it is a dis\ntinct departure for the Younger ISend farmer to appear in the role\nof corporation defender. Ada News.\nLabor isn't getting its beer, but it manages to keep up its fer\nment. Columbus (S. C.) Record.\nCTYLE HEADQUARTERS\nDwhere UoriftU. Brcmb (Slothes aresoli\n\"II\n1\n\"There is not a line in the republican platform that professes\nan emotion of pride in what America did to win the war.\" Gov\nernor Cox.\nMi\nQ A O' 6. C\"\nDecided Style Changes in\nMen's Fall Clothes\nThe designing that marks this season's models em\nbraces welcome changes a shorter vent, a lower, lesi\nrestricted waist, and a more graceful fullness to the\nentire coat.\nThere's an easy smartness about these clothes that\n6harply distinguishes them from the styles of the past\ntwo or three seasons and from the models being\nshown elsewhere this fall.\nSociety Brand Clothes maintain their style leader\nship. They are the first to break away from the in\nfluence that military uniforms have had upon clothes\nstyles styles of which men are becoming tired.\nCome in and see the latest, the final in style, in the\nmost approved of fabrics.\nIarveys'\nMX\ni.\nII\nJ\nI\n.11\n14\n.1\ni\ni\ni\nUIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIII!!!l!ill!lll!IW\nFederal Electric Washing Machine\nIt you hired an expert mechanical engineer to choo\nyour washing machine you would own a Federal, be\ncause ho wotdd be convinced of the excellent features of\nconstruction and would see SAFK1T FIRST\nTHROUGHOUT\nAll moving parts are concealed, even motor, no ex\n,posed revolving shafts. Safety Wringer, no possible\nchance of injury. Call us for demonstration and terras.\nChickasha Gas Electric Company\nPHONE 100 421 CHICKASHA AVE.\nV'lUIIIIIUIIIIIIUUIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIUIIIIIIIIM\nThere u SOLID COMFORT\nin on9 of OUR NEW HEATERS\nA HOME,\n